","1433":"1433","1388":"1388","1465":"1465","1366":"1366","1364":"1364","1406":"1406","Raby, Durham, England, United Kingdom":"Raby, Durham, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Alnwick Castle, Northumberland, England":"Alnwick Castle, Northumberland, England"},"en":{"1364–":"1364–Deceased","1358–1433":"1358–1433","1360–1447":"1360–1447","1362–Female":"1362–Deceased","1363–1425":"1363–1425","1364–Male":"1364–Deceased","1366–1406":"1366–1406","1367–1465":"1367–1465","1369–1412":"1369–1412","1270–Male":"1270–Deceased","1337–1388":"1337–1388","1335–1379":"1335–1379","1363":"1363","1362":"1362","July 1357":"July 1357","1360":"1360","1270":"1270","1337":"1337","1425":"1425","1447":"1447","1369":"1369","1358":"1358","1379":"1379","1335":"1335","1412":"1412","1367":"1367","1433":"1433","1388":"1388","1465":"1465","1366":"1366","1364":"1364","1406":"1406","Raby, Durham, England, United Kingdom":"Raby, Durham, England, United Kingdom","Alnwick Castle, Northumberland, England":"Alnwick Castle, Northumberland, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Earl","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: nickname from Middle English <i>e(o)rl</i> ‘earl’, a traditional English title of nobility equivalent in rank to French and Norman   Count  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Earle","meanings":["English: variant of   Earl  ."]},{"name":"Harle","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Dieter, Johann, Kurt.","South German (<b>Härle</b>): nickname from a diminutive of Middle High German <i>hār</i> ‘hair’.","English (northern) and Scottish: habitational name from Kirkharle and Little Harle in Northumberland (earlier simply <i>Herle</i>, <i>Harle</i>), possibly named from an Old English personal name <i>Herela</i> (a derivative of various compound names with the first element <i>here</i> ‘army’) + Old English <i>lēah</i> ‘wood, clearing’."]},{"name":"Earls","meanings":["English: variant of   Earl   with genitival <i>-s</i>, denoting someone who was a member of an earl's household, or, with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. In Ireland, when this is not the English name, it is from Gaelic <b>Mac an Iarla</b> ‘son of the earl’."]},{"name":"Hearl","meanings":["English: variant of   Earl   with prosthetic <i>H-</i>."]},{"name":"Count","meanings":["English: nickname from Anglo-Norman French <i>counte</i> ‘count’ (Old French <i>conte</i>, from Latin <i>comes</i>, <i>comitem</i>); a title of French and Norman nobility, ranking as equivalent to English   Earl  ."]},{"name":"Earll","meanings":["English (Kent): variant of   Earl  ."]}]},{"name":"of","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese: Cheng, Jing, Kam Fung, Wai Shing, Wing, Yali, Yuk.","Chinese:","variant Romanization of the surnames 歐 and 區, see   Ou   1 and 2."],"variants":[{"name":"Ou","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Wei, Ying, Ching, Heng, Hong, Jia, Kuang Yu, Li-Ching, Cho, Chong, Chung, Sa.  Southeast Asian Lichun, Ming, Quan, Roeun, Sokhom, Chau, Hai, Leang, Ly, Nhanh, Phan, Pho, Tha.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 歐, meaning ‘to sing someone's praise’ in ancient Chinese: (i) from the placename Dong Ou (東甌), a fief (in present-day Wenzhou in Zhejiang province) which was granted to Yao in 192  BC . It is said that Yao was a descendant of Wujiang (reigned 355–333  BC ), king of the state of Yue (located mainly in present-day Zhejiang and Jiangxi provinces) during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ). (ii) from the placename Ou Yu (歐餘), the name of a fief (located in present-day Zhejiang province) that was granted to Ti, the second son of Wujiang (reigned 355–333  BC ), king of the state of Yue (located mainly in present-day Zhejiang and Jiangxi provinces) during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ).","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 區, originally denoting an ancient vessel for measurement in ancient Chinese: from the personal name of <i>Ou Zhizi</i> (歐治子), an expert sword-maker who lived during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ). Some of his descendants inherited <i>Ou</i> (歐) as their surname, simplifying the Chinese character 歐 to 區."]}]},{"name":"Westmor","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Isle of Wight): topographic name for someone who lived ‘by the western moor’ (Middle English <i>mor</i> ‘heath, swamp, fen’)."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Neville","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Irish (of Norman origin): habitational name from Neuville in Calvados or Néville in Seine-Maritime, both so called from Old French <i>neu(f)</i> ‘new’ (from Latin <i>novus</i>) + <i>ville</i> ‘settlement’. One family line, originally from Neuville (Calvados), became powerful during the Wars of the Roses through Richard <i>Neville</i> (1428–71), 16th Earl of Warwick, nicknamed \"The Kingmaker\".","Irish (Munster): assimilation of the Gaelic name <b>Ó Niadh</b> (see   Nee  ) and sometimes of <b>Ó Cnaimhín</b> (see   Nevin  ).","History: George Neville came to VA in or <i>c.</i> 1700 and settled on the headwaters of the Occoquan River, acquiring a large estate. His descendants, bearing the surnames Neville and Craig, were of considerable importance in Pittsburgh, PA, and Cincinnati, OH."],"variants":[{"name":"Nevells","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Neville  ."]},{"name":"Nevils","meanings":["English: variant of   Neville  ."]},{"name":"Novel","meanings":["English: variant of   Neville  .","Catalan: variant of   Novell  ."]},{"name":"Newell","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Neville  .","English: variant of   Noel  .","English: variant of   Newhall  ."]},{"name":"Nevills","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Neville  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Nevil","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Neville  ."]},{"name":"Newill","meanings":["English and Irish (or Norman origin): variant of   Neville  ."]},{"name":"Nevill","meanings":["English and Irish: of Norman origin, a variant of   Neville  ."]},{"name":"Nevels","meanings":["English and Scottish (Wigtownshire): of Norman origin, a variant of   Neville  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. This surname is now rare in Britain.","Dutch and North German: unexplained."]},{"name":"Nee","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Dermot, John Patrick.","Irish (Galway): shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Niadh</b> ‘descendant of <i>Nia</i>’ or <b>Mac Niadh</b> ‘son of <i>Nia</i>’. Compare   McNee  .   Needham   2 and   Neville   have also been adopted as Anglicized forms of this name.","North German: possibly a relationship name from Middle Low German <i>neve</i> ‘nephew, grand-child’."]}]},{"name":"Ralph","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From a Norman French name, <i>Raulf</i>, a contracted form of the Germanic personal name <i>Radulf</i>, derived from <i>rād</i> ‘counsel’ + <i>wulf</i> ‘wolf’. The spelling with <i>-ph</i> is due to classical influence in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Ralf","meanings":["From a Norman French name, <i>Raulf</i>, a contracted form of the Germanic personal name <i>Radulf</i>, derived from <i>rād</i> ‘counsel’ + <i>wulf</i> ‘wolf’. The spelling with <i>-ph</i> is due to classical influence in the 18th century."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Ralph Earl of Westmor de Neville was born in 1364, in Raby, Durham, England, United Kingdom, his father, John Neville, was 27 and his mother, Maud de Percy, was 30. He had at least 1 son."},"et":{"1364–":"1364–Surnud","1358–1433":"1358–1433","1360–1447":"1360–1447","1362–Female":"1362–Surnud","1363–1425":"1363–1425","1364–Male":"1364–Surnud","1366–1406":"1366–1406","1367–1465":"1367–1465","1369–1412":"1369–1412","1270–Male":"1270–Surnud","1337–1388":"1337–1388","1335–1379":"1335–1379","1363":"1363","1362":"1362","July 1357":"juuli 1357","1360":"1360","1270":"1270","1337":"1337","1425":"1425","1447":"1447","1369":"1369","1358":"1358","1379":"1379","1335":"1335","1412":"1412","1367":"1367","1433":"1433","1388":"1388","1465":"1465","1366":"1366","1364":"1364","1406":"1406","Raby, Durham, England, United Kingdom":"Raby, Durham, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Alnwick Castle, Northumberland, England":"Alnwick Castle, Northumberland, England"},"fi":{"1364–":"1364–Kuollut","1358–1433":"1358–1433","1360–1447":"1360–1447","1362–Female":"1362–Kuollut","1363–1425":"1363–1425","1364–Male":"1364–Kuollut","1366–1406":"1366–1406","1367–1465":"1367–1465","1369–1412":"1369–1412","1270–Male":"1270–Kuollut","1337–1388":"1337–1388","1335–1379":"1335–1379","1363":"1363","1362":"1362","July 1357":"heinäkuu 1357","1360":"1360","1270":"1270","1337":"1337","1425":"1425","1447":"1447","1369":"1369","1358":"1358","1379":"1379","1335":"1335","1412":"1412","1367":"1367","1433":"1433","1388":"1388","1465":"1465","1366":"1366","1364":"1364","1406":"1406","Raby, Durham, England, United Kingdom":"Raby, Durham, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningask